cholars assess and critique her efforts to revitalize critical theory.Jaeggi’s innovative work reclaims key concepts of Hegelian-Marxist social philosophy and reads them through the lens of such thinkers as Adorno, Heidegger, and Dewey, while simultaneously putting them into dialogue with contemporary analytic philosophy. Structured for classroom use, this critical introduction to Rahel Jaeggi is an insightful and generative confrontation with the most recent transformation of Frankfurt School–inspired social and philosophical critical theory. This volume features an essay by Jaeggi on moral progress and social change, essays by leading scholars engaging with her conceptual analysis of alienation and the critique of forms of life, and a Q&A between Jaeggi and volume coeditor Amy Allen. For scholars and students wishing to engage in the debate with key contemporary thinkers over the past, present, and future(s) of critical theory, this volume will be transformative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Amy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCelikates, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaeggi, Rahel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoick, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendieta, Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendieta, Eduardo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNeuhouser, Frederick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPensky, Max, econtributor.4ctb4ht